	<section id="description">
		<h2>Late Reverberation Cancellation using Bayesian Estimation of Multi Channel Linear Predictors with Student's t Source Prior</h2>

		<div class="row">
				<div class="nine columns">
				A speech signal propagating in an enclosure undergoes multiple reflections at the walls and rigid surfaces. 
				The signal recorded using a microphone at any spatial position is due to the signal propagating directly 
				from the source position to the microphone position, and reflections from the walls. Linear model of sound 
				propagation describes the received signal at the microphone using an impulse response called the room impulse 
				response. The components due to the direct path signal, and the first few orders of reflections appear as 
				distinct impulses, where as higher order reflections appear as noise component with exponentially decaying 
				envelope. Early reflection component, which comprises of the direct component and first few orders of 
				reflections changes the timbre, hence the quality, of the signal. Intelligibility has little or no effect, and 
				in some cases the early reflections add to intelligibility due to the increased perceived loudness. The late 
				reflections, on the otherhand, smear the signal distorting the temporal modulations present in the natural 
				speech, affecting intelligibility. Late reverberation suppression is, hence, desired for many speech 
				communication applications.<br>
				Multi channel linear prediction (MCLP) in short time Fourier transform (STFT) domain based approach is considered 
				here. Late reverberation is modeled as the predictable part of the microphone signals, and the residual signal is 
				considered as the desired early reflection signal.
				<h3>Observation model</h3>
					The observed signal at a microphone in a reverberant enclosure is modeled as the convolution 
					of room impulse response with the source signal,					
						$$x_m[n]=s[n] * h_m[n]$$
				<h3>Signal model</h3>
					STFT coefficients of are modeled as Gaussian random variables with time-dependent variance. 
					The variance, being a positive quantity is modeled as a Gamma distributed random variable.				
				</div>						
		</div>

		<br>
